<p>I&rsquo;ve been browsing Emacs&rsquo;s <strong>The Info Directory</strong> (C-h i) the other day and came across a menu item called <strong>Newsticker</strong>.</p>
<p>Turned out is a built-in RSS reader I never heard of.
I know Emacs has <strong>Gnus</strong> which I tried to use as RSS reader before but didn&rsquo;t succeed.
Then, as probably most of Emacs users, I moved to <strong>Elfeed</strong> which is great.</p>
<p>Here is how Newsticker looks like:</p>
<img alt="hermit logo" src="https://codelearn.me/assets/img/newsticker-treeview.png" width="100%"/>
<p>isn&rsquo;t it nice? You can open it with <strong>M-x newsticker-show-news</strong>.</p>
<p>It&rsquo;s been a few weeks since I decided to use it.</p>
<h3 id="navigation">Navigation</h3>
<p>Navigation is very simple:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>f</strong> and <strong>F</strong> for switching feeds forward/backward</li>
<li><strong>n</strong> and <strong>p</strong> for switching posts</li>
<li><strong>&lt;RET&gt;</strong> to read full article</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="configuration">Configuration</h3>
<p>Setting feeds is only slightly different from Elfeed:</p>
<div class="highlight"><pre tabindex="0" style="color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;"><code class="language-lisp" data-lang="lisp"><span style="display:flex;"><span>(<span style="color:#66d9ef">setq</span> newsticker-url-list <span style="color:#f92672">&#39;</span>(
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span> (<span style="color:#e6db74">&#34;Planet Emacslife&#34;</span> <span style="color:#e6db74">&#34;https://planet.emacslife.com/atom.xml&#34;</span>)
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span> (<span style="color:#e6db74">&#34;&lt;name&gt;&#34;</span> <span style="color:#e6db74">&#34;&lt;url&gt;&#34;</span>)))
</span></span></code></pre></div><p>Also when <strong>q</strong> is pressed the whole Newsticker is closed BUT its buffers are still there
which I don&rsquo;t really like.</p>
<p>So I came up with this elisp:</p>
<div class="highlight"><pre tabindex="0" style="color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;"><code class="language-lisp" data-lang="lisp"><span style="display:flex;"><span>(defun my/close-newsticker ()
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span> <span style="color:#e6db74">&#34;Kill all tree-view related buffers.&#34;</span>
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span> (kill-buffer <span style="color:#e6db74">&#34;*Newsticker List*&#34;</span>)
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span> (kill-buffer <span style="color:#e6db74">&#34;*Newsticker Item*&#34;</span>)
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span> (kill-buffer <span style="color:#e6db74">&#34;*Newsticker Tree*&#34;</span>))
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span>
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span>(advice-add <span style="color:#e6db74">&#39;newsticker-treeview-quit</span> <span style="color:#e6db74">:after</span> <span style="color:#e6db74">&#39;my/close-newsticker</span>)
</span></span></code></pre></div><p>Now when <strong>newsticker-treeview-quit</strong> function is called the Newsticker buffers getting killed too.</p>
<h3 id="why-use-built-in-tools">Why use built-in tools</h3>
<p>I remember I&rsquo;ve read, I think in <a href="https://irreal.org/blog/">Irreal&rsquo;s blog</a> about not understanding some people&rsquo;s obsession to use built-in tools in Emacs.</p>
<p>I can&rsquo;t quite explain it either but I do feel drawn towards built-in tools too haha.</p>
<p>Naturally I try to track/think about every extension I add to my config
to make sure it&rsquo;s up to date, not abandoned, supports my version of emacs, how much dependencies it has, etc. And even when everything is ok, I still
feel like someone can take it from me if let&rsquo;s say a maintainer will decide to archive the project or something.</p>
<p>It just sits in my brain on the background and slowly drains my energy.
It&rsquo;s maybe silly reason but I just feel more vulnerable with more dependencies.</p>
<p>Anyways, I suggest you to try <strong>Newsticker</strong>, it&rsquo;s very interesting mode.</p>